  "prompt": "What should I expect in a Android Engineer interview at Facebook?",
  "response": "Here's what you can typically expect in an Android Engineer interview at Facebook:\n\n1. Technical Phone Screen (1-2 rounds)\n- Data structures and algorithms questions\n- Android-specific technical discussions\n- Coding on shared document/CoderPad\n- Usually 45-60 minutes per round\n\n2. On-site/Virtual On-site (4-5 rounds)\nTechnical Interviews:\n- 2-3 coding/algorithm rounds\n- Complex problem-solving\n- Data structures and algorithms\n- Code optimization\n- Live coding on whiteboard/editor\n- Focus on efficient solutions\n\nAndroid-Specific Interviews:\n- Deep Android knowledge\n- Performance optimization\n- Memory management\n- Threading/Concurrency\n- Architecture design\n- UI/UX considerations\n- Kotlin/Java proficiency\n\nSystem Design Round:\n- Design scalable Android apps\n- Discuss architectural patterns\n- Component interactions\n- Performance considerations\n- Clean architecture principles\n\nBehavioral Interviews:\n- Leadership principles\n- Problem-solving scenarios\n- Teamwork examples\n- Impact-driven projects\n- Facebook's core values\n\nKey Topics to Prepare:\n- Advanced Android concepts\n- Kotlin/Java expertise\n- Retrofit/RxJava\n- Dependency injection\n- SOLID principles\n- Design patterns\n- Performance optimization techniques\n\nRecommended Preparation:\n- LeetCode/HackerRank practice\n- System design preparation\n- Mock interviews\n- Review Facebook's engineering blog\n- Understand latest Android technologies",
